  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Stepping Stones with Children aged 5-14 years</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Across Africa, HIV and AIDS affects millions of people, leaving many children orphaned and vulnerable. Yet parents and carers can find it hard to discuss HIV with young children and there are high levels of stigma and ignorance surrounding HIV. &#x2018;Stepping Stones&#x2019; is a proven training package used in over 100 countries and available in 25 languages. It helps adults and young people explore how relations between men and women and other issues influence the way people behave, and how behaviour can be improved. In this project, The Salamander Trust is developing, for the first time, &#x2018;Stepping Stones with Children&#x2019;. This training package will help people to develop the skills to relate to younger children aged 5-14 on issues like death, disclosure of HIV status, stigma and age-appropriate information on HIV and sex. &#x2018;Stepping Stones with Children&#x2019; will give children, their families and those caring for them, the materials and skills to better relate to each other on sensitive and difficult issues.</narrative>
  </description>
